 #include <stdio.h>
        int main(int argc, char *argv[])
        {
            while (argc--)
            printf("%s\n", argv[argc]);
            return 0;
        }
/////////////  This program demonstrates how command-line arguments (argc, argv) work in C and how the loop prints them in reverse order.
2️⃣ Meaning of argc and argv
argc

Argument count

Number of command-line arguments

argv

Argument vector

Array of pointers to strings

Structure:

argv[0] → program name
argv[1] → first argument
argv[2] → second argument
...
argv[argc-1] → last argument

Example execution:

./prog apple banana mango

Then:

argc = 4

Memory layout:

argv[0] → "./prog"
argv[1] → "apple"
argv[2] → "banana"
argv[3] → "mango"
argv[4] → NULL
3️⃣ Understanding the loop
while (argc--)

Post-decrement means:

Use current value of argc

Then decrease it

Equivalent logic:

while(argc != 0)
{
    argc--;
    printf("%s\n", argv[argc]);
}
4️⃣ Iteration Example

Command:

./prog apple banana mango

Initial:

argc = 4
Iteration 1
argc-- → 4
argc becomes 3
argv[3] → "mango"

Output:

mango
Iteration 2
argc-- → 3
argc becomes 2
argv[2] → "banana"

Output:

banana
Iteration 3
argc-- → 2
argc becomes 1
argv[1] → "apple"

Output:

apple
Iteration 4
argc-- → 1
argc becomes 0
argv[0] → "./prog"

Output:

./prog
5️⃣ Final Output
mango
banana
apple
./prog

So the program prints command-line arguments in reverse order, including the program name.

6️⃣ Important Concept

argv is actually:

char *argv[]

which means:

array of pointers to char

So:

argv[i] → pointer to string
7️⃣ Equivalent for-loop

The same logic could be written as:

for(int i = argc-1; i >= 0; i--)
    printf("%s\n", argv[i]);
8️⃣ Key Interview Concept
argv[i] == *(argv + i)

Both access the same argument.

