why printing only ./a.out

Good question 👍
If your program prints only ./a.out, it means you ran the program without passing any command-line arguments.

Let’s understand clearly.

1️⃣ Your Code
#include <stdio.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    while (argc--)
        printf("%s\n", argv[argc]);
    return 0;
}
2️⃣ When you run the program like this
./a.out

No extra arguments are given.

So:

argc = 1

Memory:

argv[0] → "./a.out"
argv[1] → NULL
3️⃣ Execution of the loop

Initial value:

argc = 1
First iteration
argc-- → uses 1
argc becomes 0

Then:

argv[0] → "./a.out"

So it prints:

./a.out
Next iteration
argc = 0
while(0) → false

Loop stops.

4️⃣ Output
./a.out
5️⃣ If you pass arguments

Example:

./a.out apple mango banana

Then:

argc = 4

Memory:

argv[0] → ./a.out
argv[1] → apple
argv[2] → mango
argv[3] → banana

Output (reverse order):

banana
mango
apple
./a.out
6️⃣ Key rule
argv[0] always stores the program name

Even if you don't pass arguments.

7️⃣ How to avoid printing program name

If you only want user arguments:

for(int i = argc-1; i > 0; i--)
    printf("%s\n", argv[i]);

